Definition: [ναυαγέω] from a compound of {{g3491}} and {{g71}}; to be shipwrecked (stranded, "navigate"), literally or figuratively
[Νάρκισσος] a flower of the same name, from νάρκη (stupefaction, as a "narcotic"); Narcissus, a Roman
[ναί] a primary particle of strong affirmation; yes
[Ναθαναήλ] of Hebrew origin ({{h5417}}); Nathanaël (i.e. Nathanel), an Israelite and Christian
[Ναθάν] of Hebrew origin ({{h5416}}); Nathan, an Israelite
[Ναζωραῖος] from {{g3478}}; a Nazoræan, i.e. inhabitant of Nazareth; by extension, a Christian
[νάρδος] of foreign origin (compare {{h5373}}); "nard"
[Ναούμ] of Hebrew origin ({{h5151}}); Naum (i.e. Nachum), an Israelite
[ναός] from a primary ναίω (to dwell); a fane, shrine, temple  Compare {{g2411}}.
[Ναΐν] probably of Hebrew origin (compare {{h4999}}); Nain, a place in Palestine
[μιμνήσκω] a prolonged form of {{g3415}} (from which some of the tenses are borrowed); to remind, i.e. (middle voice) to recall to mind
[μιμητής] from {{g3401}}; an imitator
[μιμέομαι] middle voice from μῖμος (a "mimic"); to imitate
[μίσθιος] from {{g3408}}; a wage-earner
[μισθαποδότης] from {{g3409}} and {{g591}}; a renumerator
[μισθαποδοσία] from {{g3406}}; requital (good or bad)
[μισέω] from a primary μῖσος (hatred); to detest (especially to persecute); by extension, to love less
[μισθόω] from {{g3408}}; to let out for wages, i.e. (middle voice) to hire
[μισθός] apparently a primary word; pay for service (literally or figuratively), good or bad
[νεανίας] from a derivative of {{g3501}}; a youth (up to about forty years)
[νεανίσκος] from the same as {{g3494}}; a youth (under forty)
[Νεάπολις] from {{g3501}} and {{g4172}}; new town; Neapolis, a place in Macedonia
[Νεεμάν] of Hebrew origin ({{h5283}}); Neeman (i.e. Naaman), a Syrian
[ναύκληρος] from {{g3491}} and {{g2819}} ("clerk"); a captain
[ναῦς] from νάω or νέω (to float); a boat (of any size)
[ναύτης] from {{g3491}}; a boatman, i.e. seaman
[Ναχώρ] of Hebrew origin ({{h5152}}); Nachor, the grandfather of Abraham
[νεκρός] from an apparently primary νέκυς (a corpse); dead (literally or figuratively; also as noun)
[νεκρόω] from {{g3498}}; to deaden, i.e. (figuratively) to subdue
[μνῆμα] from {{g3415}}; a memorial, i.e. sepulchral monument (burial-place)
[μνημεῖον] from {{g3420}}; a remembrance, i.e. cenotaph (place of interment)
[μνᾶ] of Latin origin; a mna (i.e. mina), a certain weight

[μνάομαι] middle voice of a derivative of {{g3306}} or perhaps of the base of {{g3145}} (through the idea of fixture in the mind or of mental grasp); to bear in mind, i.e. recollect; by implication, to reward or punish Compare {{g3403}}.
[Μνάσων] of uncertain origin; Mnason, a Christian
[μνεία] from {{g3415}} or {{g3403}}; recollection; by implication, recital
[μίσθωμα] from {{g3409}}; a rented building
[μισθωτός] from {{g3409}}; a wage-worker (good or bad)
[Μιτυλήνη] for μυτιλήνη (abounding in shellfish); Mitylene (or Mytilene), a town on the island of Lesbos
[Μιχαήλ] of Hebrew origin ({{h4317}}); Michael, an archangel
[μωμάομαι] from {{g3470}}; to carp at, i.e. censure (discredit)
[μώλωψ] from μῶλος ("moil"; probably akin to the base of {{g3433}}) and probably ὤψ (the face; from {{g3700}}); a mole ("black eye") or blow-mark
[μυριάς] from {{g3463}}; a ten-thousand; by extension, a "myriad" or indefinite number
[Μύρα] of uncertain derivation; Myra, a place in Asia Minor
[μύριοι] plural of an apparently primary word (properly, meaning very many); ten thousand; by extension, innumerably many
[μυρίζω] from {{g3464}}; to apply (perfumed) unguent to
[Μυσία] of uncertain origin; Mysia, a region of Asia Minor
[μύρον] probably of foreign origin (compare {{h4753}}, {{g4666}}); "myrrh", i.e. (by implication) perfumed oil
[μυωπάζω] from a compound of the base of {{g3466}} and ὤψ (the face; from {{g3700}}); to shut the eyes, i.e. blink (see indistinctly)
[μυστήριον] from a derivative of μύω (to shut the mouth); a secret or "mystery" (through the idea of silence imposed by initiation into religious rites)
[Ναζαρέθ]   or Ναζαρέτ;  of uncertain derivation; Nazareth or Nazaret, a place in Palestine
[Ναζαρηνός] from {{g3478}}; a Nazarene, i.e. inhabitant of Nazareth
[μωρία] from {{g3474}}; silliness, i.e. absurdity
[μωρολογία] from a compound of {{g3474}} and {{g3004}}; silly talk, i.e. buffoonery
[μῶμος] perhaps from {{g3201}}; a flaw or blot, i.e. (figuratively) disgraceful person
[μωραίνω] from {{g3474}}; to become insipid; figuratively, to make (passively, act) as a simpleton
[Ναασσών] of Hebrew origin ({{h5177}}); Naasson (i.e. Nachshon), an Israelite
[Ναγγαί] probably of Hebrew origin (compare {{h5052}}); Nangæ (i.e. perhaps Nogach), an Israelite
[μωρός] probably from the base of {{g3466}}; dull or stupid (as if shut up), i.e. heedless, (morally) blockhead, (apparently) absurd
[Μωσεύς]   or Μωσῆς,  or Μωϋσῆςof Hebrew  origin; ({{h4872}}); Moseus, Moses, or Mouses (i.e. Mosheh), the Hebrew lawgiver
[μοσχοποιέω] from {{g3448}} and {{g4160}}; to fabricate the image of a bullock
[μόρφωσις] from {{g3445}}; formation, i.e. (by implication), appearance (semblance or (concretely) formula)
[μορφόω] from the same as {{g3444}}; to fashion (figuratively)
[μορφή] perhaps from the base of {{g3313}} (through the idea of adjustment of parts); shape; figuratively, nature
[μονόω] from {{g3441}}; to isolate, i.e. bereave
[μονόφθαλμος] from {{g3441}} and {{g3788}}; one-eyed
[μόνος] probably from {{g3306}}; remaining, i.e. sole or single; by implication, mere
[μόνον] neuter of {{g3441}} as adverb; merely
[μόχθος] from the base of {{g3425}}; toil, i.e. (by implication) sadness
[μόσχος] probably strengthened for όσχος (a shoot); a young bullock
[μοῦ] the simpler form of {{g1700}}; of me
[μουσικός] from Μοῦσα (a Muse); "musical", i.e. (as noun) a minstrel
[μυελός] perhaps a primary word; the marrow
[μυέω] from the base of {{g3466}}; to initiate, i.e. (by implication) to teach
[μῦθος] perhaps from the same as {{g3453}} (through the idea of tuition); a tale, i.e. fiction ("myth")
[μυκάομαι] from a presumed derivative of μύζω ( to "moo"); to bellow (roar)
[μυκτηρίζω] from a derivative of the base of {{g3455}} (meaning snout, as that whence lowing proceeds); to make mouths at, i.e. ridicule
[μυλικός] from {{g3458}}; belonging to a mill
[μύλος] probably ultimately from the base of {{g3433}} (through the idea of hardship); a "mill", i.e. (by implication), a grinder (millstone)
[μύλων] from {{g3458}}; a mill-house
[μόγις] adverb from a primary μόγος (toil); with difficulty
[μογιλάλος] from {{g3425}} and {{g2980}}; hardly talking, i.e. dumb (tongue-tied)
[μοί] the simpler form of {{g1698}}; to me
[μόδιος] of Latin origin; a modius, i.e. certain measure for things dry (the quantity or the utensil)
[μνημονεύω] from a derivative of {{g3420}}; to exercise memory, i.e. recollect; by implication, to punish; also to rehearse
[μνήμη] from {{g3403}}; memory
[μνηστεύω] from a derivative of {{g3415}}; to give a souvenir (engagement present), i.e. betroth
[μνημόσυνον] from {{g3421}}; a reminder (memorandum), i.e. record
[νέκρωσις] from {{g3499}}; decease; figuratively, impotency
[μοιχάω] from {{g3432}}; (middle voice) to commit adultery
[μοιχαλίς] a prolonged form of the feminine of {{g3432}}; an adulteress (literally or figuratively)
[μολυσμός] from {{g3435}}; a stain; i.e. (figuratively) immorality
[μομφή] from {{g3201}}; blame, i.e. (by implication), a fault
[Μολόχ] of Hebrew origin ({{h4432}}); Moloch (i.e. Molek), an idol
[μολύνω] probably from {{g3189}}; to soil (figuratively)
[μοιχός] perhaps a primary word; a (male) paramour; figuratively, apostate
[μόλις] probably by variation for {{g3425}}; with difficulty
[μοιχεία] from {{g3431}}; adultery
[μοιχεύω] from {{g3432}}; to commit adultery
[μονή] from {{g3306}}; a staying, i.e. residence (the act or the place)
[μονογενής] from {{g3441}} and {{g1096}}; only-born, i.e. sole
